message.content: For all natural numbers $n$, the sum of the expression $2 \cdot (n / (k + 1)) - 2 \cdot (n / (k + 1))$ over $k$ in the range from $0$ to $n-1$ equals $\log 4 - 1$.
For any natural number $n$, the sum $\sum_{k \in \{0, 1, \ldots, n-1\}} \left(2 \cdot \frac{n}{k + 1} - 2 \cdot \frac{n}{k + 1}\right)$ is equal to the real number $\log 4 - 1$.

For any natural number $n$, the sum of the expression $2 \left(\frac{n}{k+1}\right) - 2 \left(\frac{n}{k+1}\right)$ over all $k$ in the range from $0$ to $n-1$ is equal to the real number $\log 4 - 1$.

For any natural number $n$, the sum of the expression $2 \left(\frac{n}{k+1}\right) - 2 \left(\frac{n}{k+1}\right)$ over all $k$ in the range from $0$ to $n-1$ is equal to the real number $\log 4 - 1$.

For any natural number $n$, the sum of the expression $2 \cdot \left\lfloor \frac{n}{k + 1} \right\rfloor - 2 \cdot \left\lfloor \frac{n}{k + 1} \right\rfloor$ over $k$ from $0$ to $n-1$ is equal to $\log 4 - 1$.

For any natural number \( n \), the sum \(\sum_{k=0}^{n-1} \left(2 \cdot \left\lfloor \frac{n}{k+1} \right\rfloor - 2 \cdot \left\lfloor \frac{n}{k+1} \right\rfloor\right)\) equals the real number \(\log 4 - 1\).
The theorem states that for every natural number $n$, the sum of the expression $2 \cdot \frac{n}{k+1} - 2 \cdot \frac{n}{k+1}$ over all integers $k$ from $0$ to $n-1$ is equal to $\log 4 - 1$.

For any natural number $n$, the sum of the expression $2 \cdot \left\lfloor \frac{n}{k+1} \right\rfloor - 2 \cdot \left\lfloor \frac{n}{k+1} \right\rfloor$ over all integers $k$ from $0$ to $n-1$ is equal to $\log(4) - 1$.
For any natural number $n$, the sum of the expression $2 \cdot (n / (k + 1)) - 2 \cdot (n / (k + 1))$ over all $k$ in the range from $0$ to $n-1$ is equal to $\log 4 - 1$.
For any natural number $n$, the sum of the expression $2 \left(\frac{n}{k + 1}\right) - 2 \left(\frac{n}{k + 1}\right)$ over $k$ ranging from $0$ to $n-1$ is equal to $\log 4 - 1$.
